Homicide Reports (Part Two)

Lauren Hartman

5/6/2017

The Scenario

My main goal is determining patterns in relation to the weapon used in a murder. 14,330 observations are present for 2014. I would also like to know which model is the most accurate in determining which weapon was used in a murder.

Pulling the Dataset In

Dataset was obtained from Kaggle. Due to time contraint and processing limitations, will only be looking at homicides which occured in 2014. 2014 is the most current year available in this dataset.

newReport$Victim.Sex[is.na(newReport$Victim.Sex)] <- "Male"

Multinomial Regression Model

I will used this model to gain insight into the following relations: weapon used and victims sex weapon used and relationship between the victim and the perpetrator

library(nnet)

test <- multinom(Weapon~Victim.Sex, data = newReport)

It appears males are over fours times more likely than a female to be killed by a gun. Males are three times more likely to be killed by firearm or handgun. In general, women are more likely than males to be killed by a non-gun weapon/method.

Now the multinomial regression model will be used to look into the relation between weapon and relationship. The below code involves a piece of code which specifies stranger as the baseline. I am choosing stranger as the baseline because I wanted a non-personal baseline compared to more intimate relationships.

newReport$Relationship2 <- relevel(newReport$Relationship, ref = "Stranger")
test2 <- multinom(Weapon~Relationship2, data = newReport)

A wife is almost 194 times more likely than a stranger to be killed by poison. A son is almost 233 times more likely to be drowned to death. An employer is almost 176 times more likely to be stabbed to death. The list continues on above.

In general strangers are more likely to be killed by less personal means, such as by being shot.

Changing Factors Into Numeric Values

In order to use K Means, all variables must be numerical. R does not convert factors into numerics well, so will covert factors into characters first.

newReport$State <- as.character(newReport$State)

table(newReport$State)

Dealing With Odd Age Range

I will assume minimum age is 0 and maximum age is 99 for a victim.

newReport$Victim.Age <- ifelse(newReport$Victim.Age >= 0 & newReport$Victim.Age <= 99,
                     newReport$Victim.Age, NA)

The distribution is not normal. I will use median imputation.

median_age <- median(newReport$Victim.Age, na.rm = TRUE)

newReport$Victim.Age <- ifelse(is.na(newReport$Victim.Age), median_age, newReport$Victim.Age)

summary(newReport$Victim.Age)

Now all the variables are numerical.

Cluster Analysis

I will use K Means so I can look at recurring trends for the records present for 2014. First, I will look at the number of members present within four clusters.

set.seed(123)
angry <- newReport[1:4]
report_clusters_4 <- kmeans(angry, centers=4)
report_clusters_4$size
## [1] 5251 2156 2411 4513

Next, I will see how many members are present in five clusters.

set.seed(123)
angry <- newReport[1:4]
report_clusters_5 <- kmeans(angry, centers=5)
report_clusters_5$size
## [1] 4590 1952 2313 3727 1749

Finally, I will see the distribution when only three clusters are present.

set.seed(123)
angry <- newReport[1:4]
report_clusters_3 <- kmeans(angry, centers=3)
report_clusters_3$size
## [1] 5889 5032 3410

Using Pseudo F Statistic to Chose Best K Value

library(clusterSim)
## Loading required package: cluster
## Loading required package: MASS
## 
## This is package 'modeest' written by P. PONCET.
## For a complete list of functions, use 'library(help = "modeest")' or 'help.start()'.
a <- index.G1(angry, report_clusters_3$cluster, centrotypes="centroids") 
b <- index.G1(angry, report_clusters_4$cluster, centrotypes = "centroids")
c <- index.G1(angry, report_clusters_5$cluster, centrotypes = "centroids")

pseudoF<-c(a,b,c)
pseudoF
## [1] 8385.832 7778.072 7350.367

According to the above, I should pick K = 4.

report_clusters_4$size

The state where the crime occured and the victims age influences weapon choice in group two. The difference between cluster four and cluster two is the state variable has more influence than victims age in cluster four. This is reversed in cluster two.

Recommendations Based on the Multinomial Regression and the K Means Models

One suggestion is focus on the fact men and women are killed differently. Women tend to be killed more violently, but are not killed as often as men. Men are killed less violently, but are killed more often than women. Since relationship between the victim and the perpetrator is an important predictor of weapon choice, ensuring the general population is education on what constitutes a healthy relationship, whether intimate or not, is important. Further research should be considered on weapon trends per state so state and local police can focused the the trends relevant to their area.
